174. percurrat pulpita socco] The front part of the stage where the actors spoke was called ‘pulpitum’ by the Greeks λογεῖον. As to ‘soccus’ see S. i. 3. 127 n. It was worn by comic actors, as being a less dignified order of covering for the feet than the ‘cothurnus' There is a representation of it in the Dict. Ant. Other shoes worn in comedy were ‘baxeae’ and ‘crepidaess for the same reason, each being a loose sort of slipper, and the latter not materially different, as obser-ved be- fore, from the ‘soccus' Horace means that Dossennus is careless in the composi- tion of his plays, which he expresses by his running about the stage with loose slippers. His only care, he says, is to make money. The aediles, or any one who cared to put a new play upon the stage, paid for it.
